---

Topic 1: Web Server Brute Force Authentication

What is it?

A brute-force attack is when an attacker repeatedly tries different passwords until the correct one is found.

Example:

Username: suresh

Password attempts:
123456
password
welcome
admin123
Summer@2026
Barclays@123
...

Eventually, one password matches.


---

Types of Password Attacks

1. Brute Force

Every possible password combination is tried.

Example:

aaaa
aaab
aaac
...

Very slow but guaranteed if given enough time.


---

2. Dictionary Attack

Uses a list of common passwords.

password
welcome
qwerty
admin
letmein

Much faster than brute force.


---

3. Credential Stuffing ⭐

Uses usernames/passwords leaked from other websites.

Example:

Netflix:
suresh@gmail.com
Password123

Attacker tries same credentials on Barclays.

Works because many people reuse passwords.


---

4. Password Spraying ⭐

Instead of attacking one account with many passwords:

Suresh -> Summer2026
Rahul -> Summer2026
Divya -> Summer2026
Akhil -> Summer2026

Only one password is tried against many users, avoiding account lockouts.


---

How do companies stop these attacks?

Account Lockout

After 5 failed attempts:

Account Locked


---

Rate Limiting

Allow only a limited number of login attempts per minute.


---

CAPTCHA

Require the user to prove they are human.


---

MFA

Even if the password is stolen, a second factor is required.


---

Password Policies

Require:

Long passwords

Special characters

No common passwords



---

Why is brute force dangerous?

If an attacker logs in successfully:

They appear as a legitimate user.

No software vulnerability is needed.

They can access emails, documents, or financial data.



---

Topic 2: Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) Weaknesses

What is MFA?

Authentication uses multiple factors.

Factor 1 — Something you know

Password
PIN

Factor 2 — Something you have

Phone
Security Key
Authenticator App

Factor 3 — Something you are

Fingerprint
Face ID
Iris Scan


---

Why is MFA better?

Password only:

Password stolen
↓

Account compromised

With MFA:

Password stolen
↓

Attacker still needs
↓

OTP / Authenticator / Security Key


---

MFA Weaknesses

SIM Swapping

The attacker convinces the mobile carrier to transfer your phone number to a new SIM.

Result:

OTP now goes to attacker.


---

MFA Fatigue

The attacker repeatedly sends authentication prompts.

Approve?
Approve?
Approve?
Approve?

The user accidentally approves.


---

Phishing Proxy

A fake login page captures:

Username

Password

OTP


The attacker immediately logs in using the captured values.


---

Session Hijacking

The attacker steals an authenticated session cookie or token after MFA has already been completed.


---

Better MFA Methods

Best → Worst

Hardware Security Keys (FIDO2/WebAuthn)
↓

Authenticator Apps

↓

Push Notifications

↓

SMS OTP


